---
import SiteLayout from "../../../../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
import Breadcrumbs from "../../../../../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="How PoliceConduct.org Verifies Reports, Handles Corrections, and Builds a Durable Public Record"
  description="PoliceConduct.org explains how it reviews submissions, requests supporting detail, handles disputes and corrections, and preserves a durable public record for accountability."
  pagePath="/news/2026/03/15/how-policeconduct-org-verifies-reports-handles-corrections-and-builds-a-durable-public-record/"
>
  <main class="">
    <section class="py-vh-3 bg-gray-100 border-bottom border-dark">
      <div class="container">
        <Breadcrumbs
          items={[
            { label: "News", href: "/news/" },
            {
              label: "Verification and Corrections Policy",
              href: "/news/2026/03/15/how-policeconduct-org-verifies-reports-handles-corrections-and-builds-a-durable-public-record/",
              current: true,
            },
          ]}
        />
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-12 col-lg-10">
            <p class="text-uppercase small text-muted mb-2">News</p>
            <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold">
              How PoliceConduct.org Verifies Reports, Handles Corrections, and
              Builds a Durable Public Record
            </h1>
            <p class="lead text-muted mb-0">
              <strong>Dover, Delaware — March 15, 2026</strong> — PoliceConduct.org
              is publishing its verification and corrections approach so contributors,
              law enforcement, journalists, and the public can understand how reports
              are reviewed before publication and how the record is maintained over
              time.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="py-vh-2">
      <div class="container">
        <p>
          Police accountability work is only useful if the underlying record is
          credible. A platform that publishes everything without review becomes
          noise. A platform that hides difficult reports until every possible
          question is resolved often leaves the public with no record at all.
          PoliceConduct.org is trying to hold that line responsibly: open to
          submissions, careful about what gets published, and willing to correct
          the record when new information arrives.
        </p>

        <h2 class="h4 text-uppercase text-muted mt-5">
          What We Review Before Publication
        </h2>
        <p>
          Every submission is reviewed before it is published. We look for a
          coherent account of what happened, when it happened, where it
          happened, and which agency or officer was involved. Reports with clear
          dates, locations, names, supporting links, or uploaded evidence are
          easier to verify and move faster.
        </p>
        <p>
          We also look for internal consistency. If a timeline does not make
          sense, an agency cannot be identified, or the submission appears to
          mix firsthand knowledge with rumor, we may hold the report, request
          clarification, or decline to publish it as submitted.
        </p>

        <h2 class="h4 text-uppercase text-muted mt-5">
          What Helps a Report Move Faster
        </h2>
        <p>
          The strongest submissions usually include incident dates, agency
          names, officer names or badge numbers when known, and supporting
          material such as public records, photographs, video, court filings, or
          credible news coverage. That does not mean every valid report must
          arrive with a complete evidence package. It means specific detail
          makes review more reliable.
        </p>
        <p>
          Anonymous or partial submissions can still be important, but they are
          more likely to require follow-up before publication. When that happens
          we would rather slow down than publish something we cannot stand
          behind.
        </p>

        <h2 class="h4 text-uppercase text-muted mt-5">
          What We May Hold, Reject, or Revise
        </h2>
        <p>
          We may decline to publish reports that are too vague to verify, that
          identify the wrong person or agency, that rely on obviously false
          claims, or that appear intended to harass rather than document a real
          event. We may also edit for clarity, remove unnecessary personal
          information, or separate factual claims from opinion so the public
          record is easier to evaluate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Publication is not a statement that every allegation has been proven
          in court. It is a statement that the report met our threshold for
          public documentation based on the information available at the time.
        </p>

        <h2 class="h4 text-uppercase text-muted mt-5">
          How Corrections and Disputes Work
        </h2>
        <p>
          A durable public record has to be correctable. If a reporter, witness,
          officer, agency, attorney, or member of the public provides credible
          new information, we review it. That can lead to a correction, a
          clarification, an added update, or removal of material that should not
          have been published in its original form.
        </p>
        <p>
          Not every disagreement is a correction. Some disputes turn on
          interpretation rather than factual error. In those cases, the right
          response may be to add context rather than erase the original report.
          The goal is not to freeze the first version forever. The goal is to
          preserve an honest record of what was reported and what later became
          known.
        </p>

        <blockquote class="border border-1 rounded-3 p-3 bg-white text-muted">
          <p class="mb-0">
            "People should not need money, media access, or a lawyer to keep a
            serious police interaction from disappearing. But if we are going to
            preserve that record, we also have to take verification and
            corrections seriously."
          </p>
        </blockquote>

        <h2 class="h4 text-uppercase text-muted mt-5">
          Why a Durable Record Matters
        </h2>
        <p>
          Many police interactions are never fully captured in official
          narratives, and many public controversies fade before a pattern
          becomes visible. PoliceConduct.org exists so those experiences are not
          lost. That includes negative interactions, but it also includes
          commendable conduct that deserves to be visible and repeatable.
        </p>
        <p>
          Accountability depends on memory. Public trust depends on accuracy.
          The project is built around both.
        </p>

        <h2 class="h4 text-uppercase text-muted mt-5">How to Help</h2>
        <p>
          If you submit a report, the most helpful thing you can do is be as
          specific as possible. If you see an error, send a correction with the
          strongest supporting information you have. If you are an attorney,
          researcher, journalist, or community volunteer who wants to help
          review and strengthen the public record, PoliceConduct.org would like
          to hear from you.
        </p>
        <p>
          To submit a report, suggest a correction, or contact the team, visit
          <a href="https://policeconduct.org" class="link-dark"
            ><strong>PoliceConduct.org</strong></a
          >.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</SiteLayout>
